definitely the 2008 crisis. With the rest of the Eurozone region facing a major financial crisis, Greece became ground zero in 2009. The Greek government failed to balance its economy and unsustainable budget debts led to the country’s debt crisis. This resulted in Greeks relying on EU bailout programmes that forced them to accept a bailout package with tough austerity measures.

On the 25th of November 2019, the Greek people went to the ballots and elected a new government under the leadership of Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis. Greece’s Economic Bulletin survey (an organisation that forecasts the economy’s path) suggests that growth will continue to advantage and extend into next year. A survey for Medcap, the consulting unit of ECS for foreign investors, found that Medcap led Greece’s position against the rest of the world in three categories, specifically in terms of accessible business bureaucracy, goods and services price and public sector efficiency.

2019 recognised victory

UK equity investors recognized the crucial political shift that took place in Greece. The election benefited the Greek stock market (Athex Composite Index) by 15% and the Euro Stoxx 600 Index by 13.5%, during the first ten months of 2019, the best returns from the European equity market. From then on, the winning wave kept rolling.
